Host plant Chusquea scandens ( Poaceae ); host Lepidoptera : Scoturopsis Hering sp. ( Notodontidae ); time span from pupation to emergence: about 5 weeks for females, unknown for the male. The parasitoid cuts a radial opening at posterior side of the mummy releasing a "lid" , comprinsing the anal apex of mummified caterpillar, before emergence. The mummy exit mode of this species is unique for the genus, since all previously known mummies produced by Aleiodes species had a posterior hole cut for emergence (
Zaldivar-Riveron et al. 2008
).
